John Edward: “Language is a vital skill for the world’s citizens”
Scottish Independent Schools broke their academic record in 2018 and once again demonstrated outstanding exam results, reinforced by individual and collective achievements in sports, arts, music and other community merits.
With a total of more than 30,000 students enrolled across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the highest possible level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers, and to be global citizens.
Working in the education sector, which can design and implement the planned school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and willingly chosen in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you can talk to a person in a language he understands, he will understand you with his mind.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will speak to his heart.”
It is a strong reminder that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships and build trust in people from other countries.
According to the results of recent exams this year, we can say that languages are at the peak of popularity and have the best passing ratings in independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who learned a foreign language received the highest A rating.
The data collected from the 74 schools that are members of SCIS showed that 72 percent of students received the highest grade A in the Mandarin language exam, 72 percent received the highest grade A in German, and 69 percent received the highest grade A in French and 63 percent in Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland see foreign language skills as an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as an optional subject are now considered as important as basic subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school programmes and elsewhere.
According to a 2014 survey by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills, 17 percent of all reasons employers struggled to fill jobs were insufficient language skills.
Therefore, linguistic skills are becoming increasingly necessary to prepare young people for their future careers.
As future employability will depend heavily on languages, these skills are becoming essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career a person chooses to pursue with a second language, he or she will be much better off in the future if he or she possesses these lifelong skills.
By being able to communicate directly with people from abroad, a person who learns several languages will be much more competitive.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to participate in the interview, while French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of people, i.e. 15 percent.
That is why investing in language teaching is important for the children of today.
By learning several languages, especially in developing countries, children will have better opportunities for meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school differs according to the languages it teaches.
Many schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK in view of the future 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests, there will always be plenty of languages to choose from in an independent school with teaching staff and specialists in the field.
Scottish independent schools are ready to create a teaching environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to live in the future.
It is undeniable that in today’s global business environment, languages remain vital for the country’s future, so this must be reflected in the education system as well.
In fact, modern languages should certainly be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and results to young people in Scotland.
This must be done.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
