North Korea says it won’t disarm unilaterally
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were fuelling their distrust of the United States and that the country would not give up nuclear weapons unilaterally in such circumstances.
Ri said North Korea had taken "significant measures of goodwill" in recent years, such as halting nuclear missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test base and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"But we have not received a similar response from the U.S. side," he said.
“Without any confidence in the United States, we will not be able to rely on our national security, and under such circumstances we will not be the first to disarm unilaterally.”
While Ri repeated North Korea’s complaints about Washington’s opposition to a staged approach to nuclear disarmament that would reward North Korea by taking steps, his statement stood out in that he did not completely reject the idea of bilateral disarmament, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim and Donald Trump at the first meeting between the US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work on "the disarmament of the Korean peninsula" and Trump pledged to ensure North Korea's security.
North Korea seeks a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused to relax tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States is demanding nuclear disarmament first and is increasing pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal by means of coercive methods, even by refusing to declare the end of the war,” he said.
“To think that sanctions can bring us to our knees is like people who don’t care about pursuing utopian dreams.
But the problem is that the continuing sanctions are deepening our distrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second Kim-Trump meeting, highlighted by the U.S. leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, he stressed three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months: “If the other country on this issue of nuclear disarmament were South Korea rather than the US, the issue of nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a dead end.”
But the tone of Ri's speech has changed dramatically since last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that when "Mr. Evil President" Trump called Kim a "missile gentleman" on a suicide mission, targeting North Korea's missiles to the US was absolutely inevitable.
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps towards disarmament, but said there was still a long way to go and that sanctions should be maintained until North Korea meets nuclear disarmament requirements.
Trump said Wednesday he had no timetable, saying "if it takes two years, three years, or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia said the UN Security Council should repay Pyongyang for its actions.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pomeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that “the Security Council’s sanctions must be resolutely continued without any concessions until the full and definitive evidence-based nuclear disarmament is achieved.”
The Security Council has unanimously approved sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to prevent funding Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the backstage of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to loosen the ground for another meeting.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but the trip has been a failure.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying all the progress was only for North Korea to announce in a few hours that he had made "gangster claims."
North Korea said at a meeting with Moon this month it would dismantle the missile base and nuclear facility if the United States took "appropriate measures".
Kim said the “adequate measures” he sought were security guarantees promised by Trump in Singapore and a move to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Learn to Rest Enough
A new course at Harvard University this year encouraged all of its students to sleep more to combat the growing macho culture in studies, caffeine intake and waking up at night.
One academic found that students at the world’s best university often don’t even have the basic knowledge of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at the Harvard Medical School and a specialist in women's hospitals in Brigham City, has prepared a course that he says is the first of its kind in the United States.
The inspiration to prepare this course came after a talk about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of the talk, one girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I only being told about this now, in the last year of my studies?’
She said no one had told her about the importance of sleep, and that surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course is offered for the first time this year. It explains to students how the most important quality sleeping habits help to achieve academic and sports results and improve general well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University's health services department, said the university decided to offer the course after it turned out that students had a severe weekly sleep deprivation.
The hour-long course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a photo of a dormitory room where students can click a cup of coffee, curtains, simulators, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine, light, how lack of sleep affects sports performance, and how important a sleeping routine is.
In the next section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Student campus map with interactive icons that encourage participants to reflect on their daily routine.
"We understand that this will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know about the health consequences when you choose to smoke,” Professor Czeisler explained.
The culture of pride in waking up at night, he said, still exists. Modern technology and increasing pressure have led students to the ever-growing problem of sleep deprivation.
“Ensuring that you get enough and quality sleep should be students’ secret weapon in combating stress, exhaustion and anxiety,” he said, “even avoiding weight gain because lack of sleep turns the brain into a fasting mode, so students are constantly feeling hungry.”
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Zeisler prepare the course when he attended one of the courses he taught last year, his first year in Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to ask for a course available to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to invite all postgraduate students to attend this course before attending this competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set up an alarm clock when to go to bed, just as they do when they wake up, and beware of the harmful effects of blue light emitted by electronic devices and LED lights, as they can blow your circadian rhythm out of balance, making it difficult to fall asleep.
