New Cancer Vaccine Could Teach Immune System to See Bad Cells
New Cancer Vaccine Could Teach Immune System to See Bad Cells and Kill Them
Vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize bad cells as part of treatment
The method involves extracting immune cells from the patient and replacing them in the laboratory
The cells can then “see” the proteins that are found in many cancers, and then be injected back again.
The trial vaccine produced promising results in treating patients with various cancers.
In one woman treated with this vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize bad cells, ovarian cancer has disappeared for more than 18 months.
The method involves extracting the immune cells from the patient and replacing them in the laboratory, so that the cells can see the proteins that are characteristic of HER2 type cancers, and then inject them back.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “The results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine.”
“HER2 promotes the growth of several types of cancer, including breast, ovaries, lungs and rectum,” explained Professor Berzofsky.
A similar approach, where immune cells are extracted from patients and trained to target cancer cells, has been successfully applied in the treatment of leukaemia.
